[[Image:Countries by carbon dioxide emissions world map deobfuscated.png|thumb|upright=2|Countries by carbon dioxide emissions in thousands of tonnes per annum, via the burning of fossil fuels (blue the highest and green the lowest).]] [[File:Co2-2013-top40.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Carbon dioxide emissions for the top 40 countries by total emissions in 2013, given as totals and per capita. Data from EU Edgar database<ref name="EDG" />]] [[File:Co2 cumulative emissions 1970-2013.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|The cumulative {{CO2}} emissions between 1970 and 2013 from the top 40 countries in the world, including some extra-national bodies. The data comes from the EU EDGAR database<ref name="EDG">[http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts_pc1990-2013 CO2 time series 1990-2013 per capita for world countries] [[Joint Research Centre|EDGAR]] Last update: 30/10/2017</ref>]] [[File:Carbon dioxide emissions due to consumption in China.png|thumb|upright=1.5|China {{CO2}} emission in millions of tonnes from 1980 to 2009.]] This is a '''list of sovereign states and territories by [[carbon dioxide]] emissions''' due to certain forms of human activity, based on the EDGAR database created by [[European Commission]] and [[Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency]] released in 2015. The following table lists the 2015 annual {{CO2}} emissions estimates (in thousands of {{CO2}} tonnes) along with a list of emissions per capita (in tonnes of {{CO2}} per year) from same source. The data only considers carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of [[fossil fuels]] and [[cement industry|cement manufacture]], but not emissions from [[land use, land-use change and forestry]]. Emissions from international shipping or [[bunker fuel]]s are also not included in national figures,<ref name="Schrooten2">{{cite journal | last = Schrooten | first = L | title = Inventory and forecasting of maritime emissions in the Belgian sea territory, an activity based emission model | journal = Atmospheric Environment | volume = 42 | pages = 667–676 | year = 2008 | url = | doi = 10.1016/j.atmosenv.2007.09.071 | pmid = | month = | last2 = De Vlieger | first2 = Ina | last3 = Int Panis | first3 = Luc | last4 = Styns, R. Torfs | first4 = K | last5 = Torfs | first5 = R}}</ref> which can make a large difference for small countries with important ports. The top 10 largest emitter countries account for 67.6% of the world total. Since 2006, China has been emitting more {{CO2}} than any other country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/25/business/china-davos-climate-change.html|title=China's Emissions: More Than U.S. Plus Europe, and Still Rising|website=[[New York Times]]|language=en|date=2018-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/chinese-coal-fuels-rise-in-global-carbon-emissions-2j0kvrd2z|title=Chinese coal fuels rise in global carbon emissions|website=[[The Times]]|language=en|date=2017-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rrapier/2017/10/24/yes-the-u-s-leads-all-countries-in-reducing-carbon-emissions/#69229dfc3535|title=Yes, The U.S. Leads All Countries In Reducing Carbon Emissions|website=[[Forbes]]|language=en|date=2017-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2011/jan/31/world-carbon-dioxide-emissions-country-data-co2|title=World carbon dioxide emissions data by country: China speeds ahead of the rest|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|date=2011-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbl.nl/en/dossiers/Climatechange/Chinanowno1inCO2emissionsUSAinsecondposition|title=China now no. 1 in CO2 emissions; USA in second position|website=PBL [[Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency]]|language=en|date=}}</ref> Other powerful, more potent [[greenhouse gases]], including [[methane]], are not included in this data.
