The following is a list of [[old-growth forest]]s in the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]. Old growth is defined as those forests that have not been logged (and have not been significantly disturbed by human beings) in the last 150 years. "Virgin forests" are those old-growth forests that show no sign of having ever been logged.
A total of {{convert|2742|acre|ha}} of old-growth forest has been identified in Massachusetts.<ref name = "OldGrowthEastUS">{{cite web |url=http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/survey.html |title=Old Growth in the East: A Survey |author=Mary Byrd Davis |date= 23 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217114843/http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/survey.html |archivedate=17 February 2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> Massachusetts' old growth occurs almost entirely within the [[Northeastern Highlands (ecoregion)|Northeastern Highlands]] ecoregion. The following list identifies some of the sites and their locations:<ref name = "DamatoMassachesetts"> {{cite journal |last = D'Amato |first = A. |author2=Orwig, D. |author3=Foster, D. |year = 2006 |title = New Estimates of Massachusetts Old-growth Forests: Useful Data for Regional Conservation and Forest Reserve Planning |journal = [[Northeastern Naturalist]] |volume = 13 |issue = 4 |pages = 495–506 |url = http://harvardforest.fas.harvard.edu/publications/pdfs/DAmato_NENaturalist_2006.pdf |accessdate = 2008-12-31 |doi = 10.1656/1092-6194(2006)13[495:NEOMOF]2.0.CO;2 }} </ref>
